robe |url-access=registration |year=1988 |location=New York |publisher=Morrow |isbn=978-0-688-06869-1 |oclc=17260252 |ol=4127115W |lccn=87031153 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Vaillant |first=George E. |authorlink=George Eman Vaillant |title=The Natural History of Alcoholism Revisited |location=Cambridge, Mass |publisher=Harvard University Press |year=1995 |oclc=31605790 |isbn=978-0-674-60377-6|ref=harv|title-link=The Natural History of Alcoholism Revisited }}\n* {{cite book | last = Wilcox | first = D.M. | title = Alcoholic thinking: Language, culture, and belief in Alcoholics Anonymous | year = 1998 | location = [[Westport, CT]] | publisher = Greenwood Publishing Group | isbn = 978-0-275-96049-0 | ref = harv | url = https://archive.org/details/alcoholicthinkin00wilc }}\n* {{cite book|last1=Kurtz|first1=Ernest|title=Not-God: a history of Alcoholics Anonymous|publisher=Hazelden Pittman|location=Center City, Minn|year=1991|isbn=978-0894860652|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/notgodhistoryofa00kurt}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alcoholics Anonymous}}\n* [http://www.aa.org/ AA official website]\n* [http://aaagnostica.org/a-history-of-agnostic-groups-in-aa/ A History of Agnostic Groups in AA]\n* [https://biblio.wiki/wiki/Alcoholics_Anonymous_(Original_Manuscript)_1938 Original 1938 Manuscript] available at Biblio.wiki (public domain)\n\n{{Alcoholics Anonymous}}\n{{Alcohealth}}\n\n[[Category:Alcoholics Anonymous| ]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1935]]\n[[Category:Therapeutic community]]\n[[Category:Twelve-step programs]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Fixed cite error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcoholics_Anonymous"}
{"title_page": "Wexit Canada", "text_new": "{{Original research|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Wexit Canada\n| native_name =\n| slogan = \"The West Wants Out\"\n| _subheader =\n| logo = Wexitcanadablackandwhite.png\n| logo_size =\n| leader = Peter Downing\n| president =\n| spokesperson =\n| leader1_title =\n| leader1_name =\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|2020|01|12}}\n| dissolution =\n| merger =\n| split =\n| predecessor =\n| merged =\n| successor =\n| headquarters = [[Leduc, Alberta]]\n| ideology = {{ubl|[[Western alienation|Western separatism]]<ref name=\"The plan\"/><ref name=\"Wexit Party can now run for federal elections\"/>|[[Conservatism]]<ref name=\"Wexit rally\"/>|[[Right-wing populism]]}}\n| position = [[Right wing]] to [[Far right]]\n| national =\n| international =\n| student_wing =\n| membership =\n| membership_year =\n| colours = Black\n| colorcode = #000001\n| blank1_title = Fiscal policy\n| blank1 =\n| blank2_title = Social policy\n| blank2 =\n| seats2_title = Seats in the<br />[[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|0|105|hex=#000000}}\n| seats1_title = Seats in the <br>[[Senate of Canada|Senate]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|0|338|hex=#000000}}\n| website = {{URL|wexitcanada.com}}\n| country = Canada\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Wexit Canada''' is a Canadian [[List of federal political parties in Canada|federal political party]]. It advocates for the secession of [[Western Canada]], which includes [[British Columbia]], [[Alberta]], [[Saskatchewan]] and [[Manitoba]]. The name is a play on [[Brexit]], the withdrawal of the United Kingdom from the European Union.<ref>{{cite news |title='Wexit' should heed pitfalls faced by other separatist movements: experts |url=https://vancouverisland.ctvnews.ca/wexit-should-heed-pitfalls-faced-by-other-separatist-movements-experts-1.4741887 |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |publisher=[[CTV News]]}}</ref>\n\nThe party planned to run 104 candidates across the four provinces in 2020 and to run candidates for the provincial levels of government.<ref name=\"Wexit Party can now run for federal elections\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/wexit-peter-downing-western-separatism-elections-canada-1.5423793 |title=Wexit party granted eligibility for next federal election |last=Dryden |first=Joel |work=[[CBC News]] |date=January 11, 2020 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"FedProv\" /> The group initially gained traction in October 2019, shortly after the [[2019 Canadian federal election]], when the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]] under [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] [[Justin Trudeau]] was re-elected to form government.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Macvicar |first1=Adam |title=Wexit political party can now run candidates in Canadian federal elections |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6395322/wexit-political-partycanadian-federal-party-status/ |work=[[Global News]] |date=January 10, 2020 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bogart |first=Nicole |title=Wexit: How a political divide in Western Canada is driving calls for separation |url=https://election.ctvnews.ca/wexit-how-a-political-divide-in-western-canada-is-driving-calls-for-separation-1.4651085 |work=[[CTV News]] |date=October 22, 2019 |accessdate=January 13, 2020}}</ref> As of early 2020, the party started purchasing billboards in Alberta criticizing Trudeau, sparking public discussion over the lack of representation in western Canada.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://edmonton.ctvnews.ca/wexit-canada-becomes-eligible-federal-political-party-1.4763442 |title=Wexit Canada becomes eligible federal political party |last=Antoneshyn |first=Alex |website=CTV News Edmonton |date=January 12, 2020 |publisher=Bell Media |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> The party is currently led by former [[Christian Heritage Party of Canada|Christian Heritage]] candidate Peter Downing.<ref name=\"FedProv\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/wexit-rally-calgary-1.5362624 |title=Wexit party to run federal and provincial candidates across Western Canada |last=Rieger |first=Sarah |work=[[CBC News]] |date=November 17, 2019 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The party conducted a minor protest in [[Edmonton]], involving approximately 100 supporters.<ref name=\"Wexit rally\">{{Cite web |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6399314/wexit-referendum-edmonton-protest/ |title='We're looking for our own country': Wexit supporters brave cold in Edmonton for referendum protest Saturday |website=Global News |publisher=Corus Media |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Western separation ==\nWexit Canada's operators plan for their federal-level party to be used as a \"shield\" for smaller provincial operations. No [[member of parliament]] in the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] openly sympathizes with the idea of secession. The party wants a presence in the House to advance its goals. The party says it lacks enough momentum in [[Manitoba]] to achieve its goals there; however, it has larger pockets of support in the other three provinces.<ref name=\"The plan\">{{Cite web |url=http://wexitcanada.com/wexit-the-plan.pdf |title=Wexit The Plan |website=Wexit Canada |publisher=Wexit Canada |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Toneguzzi |first=Mario |title='Everyone\u2019s angry': Why you're wrong if you think Wexit is just 'an Alberta thing' |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/everyones-angry-why-youre-wrong-if-you-think-wexit-is-just-an-alberta-thing |date=November 26, 2019 |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=[[National Post]]}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n== Provincial parties ==\n\n=== Alberta ===\nThe Wexit Party is registered as a provincial party \"Wexit Alberta\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://wexitalberta.com/ |title=Wexit Alberta |website=Wexit Alberta |publisher=Wexit Alberta |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> According to its constitution, its plans include abolishing the provincial branch of the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police|RCMP]] and the establishment of an \"Alberta National Police\" and a \"Provincial Sheriff Program\". It plans to adopt an official currency to replace the [[Canadian dollar]] as well.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://wexitalberta.com/constitution.html |title=Wexit Alberta Constitution |publisher=Wexit Alberta |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://wexitalberta.com/platform.html |title=Wexit Alberta Platform |publisher=Wexit Alberta |access-date=February 3, 2020}}</ref> [[Barry Cooper (political scientist)|Barry Cooper]], a political scientist formerly of the [[University of Calgary]] who supports Western separation, said of western and eastern Canada's separate cultures in an interview with [[BBC]], \"It\u2019s a failure of trying to understand the other\u2014we don\u2019t share the same myths about what the country looks like, and we never have.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Levinson-King |first1=Robin |title=Wexit: Why some Albertans want to separate from Canada |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49899113 |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=October 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== British Columbia ===\nWexit BC is a registered party with [[Elections BC]]. Its leader is Lee Smith.<ref>{{cite web |last1=[[Elections BC]] |title=Registered Political Parties - Information |url=https://elections.bc.ca/docs/fin/Registered-Political-Parties-Information.pdf |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |work=[[Elections BC]] |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://wexitbc.org |title=Wexit British Columbia |website=Wexit British Columbia |publisher=Wexit British Columbia |date=2019 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Saskatchewan ===\nThe day after the 2019 federal election, [[Scott Moe]], [[premier of Saskatchewan]], proposed a \"New Deal\" with the federal government. He called for an end to the federal carbon tax, renegotiation of the equalization formula, and action on oil-pipeline projects.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/moe-new-deal-fire-western-alienation-1.5330659 |title=Premier Moe demands 'new deal,' says he is handing Justin Trudeau a 'fire extinguisher' |last=Hunter |first=Adam |work=[[CBC News]] |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> In the weeks after the election, Wexit volunteers began collecting signatures to form a new party. They called on Moe to hold a referendum on separation, saying that if he did not agree they would form a party to do so.<ref>{{Cite news |last=White-Crummey |first=Arthur |url=https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/wexit-party-registration-drive-coming-to-saskatchewan |title=Wexit party registration drive coming to Saskatchewan |work=[[Regina Leader-Post]] |date=November 8, 2019 |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Wiens |first=Colton |url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/wexit-saskatchewan-gathers-signatures-to-form-new-party-1.4689991 |title=Wexit Saskatchewan gathers signatures to form new party |work=[[CTV News]] |date=November 17, 2019 |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, 2020, Wexit Saskatchewan became registered as a provincial party with [[Elections Saskatchewan]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Charlton |first=Jonathan |url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/wexit-saskatchewan-gets-official-party-status-1.4847135 |title=Wexit Saskatchewan slams Moe, Sask Party as it applies for official party status |work=[[CTV News]] |date=March 10, 2020 |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=CBC News |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/wexit-saskatchewan-official-party-1.5492781 |title=Wexit Saskatchewan becomes official political party |work=[[CBC News]] |date=March 10, 2020 |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Its leader is Jake Wall.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Elections Saskatchewan |url=https://www.elections.sk.ca/candidates-political-parties/political-parties |title=Registered Political Parties |work=[[Elections Saskatchewan]] |date=2020 |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Elections Saskatchewan |url=https://cdn.elections.sk.ca/upload/RPP-Info-for-Website-2020.03.10.pdf |title=Registered Political Parties (as of March 10, 2020) |work=[[Elections Saskatchewan]] |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Once registered, Wexit Saskatchewan proposed a referendum on independence in its platform.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Wexit Saskatchewan |url=http://wexitsask.com/services.html |title=Platform |work=Wexit Saskatchewan |date=2020 |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Anti-Trudeau billboards ==\nIn early 2020, billboards that called for Trudeau's jailing appeared around Alberta, including [[Calgary]] and [[Edmonton]]. The billboards sparked an uproar and support on social media.<ref name=CTVCalgary/><ref name=\"CBC Calgary\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/trudeau-peter-downing-alberta-fights-back-signpatico-1.5424267 |title=After anti-Trudeau billboards spark outrage, ad company says it will re-evaluate vetting process |date=January 12, 2020 |access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> Those billboards pointed to the Wexit Party's website and were purchased though Signpatico, an advertising agency based in [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]]. Signpatico promised to vet future ads more carefully and stated, \"We do fundamentally stand by freedom of expression, as per the [[Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|charter]]. But we're not intending on inciting perceptions of hate speech or offensive ads.\"<ref name=\"CTVCalgary\">{{Cite news |url=https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/mobile/anti-trudeau-billboards-advertising-alberta-wexit-campaign-cause-an-uproar-1.4763332 |title=Anti-Trudeau billboards advertising Alberta Wexit campaign cause an uproar |last=Franklin |first=Michael |date=January 11, 2020 |work=CTV News |access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Canada|Politics}}\n* [[Western alienation]]\n* [[Alberta separatism]]\n* [[Cascadia (independence movement)]]\n* [[Western Block Party]]\n* [[Western Canada Concept]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Canadian federal political parties}}\n\n[[Category:2020 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2020]]\n[[Category:Secessionist organizations in Canada]]\n[[Category:Federal political parties in Canada]]\n[[Category:Regionalist parties]]\n[[Category:Pro-independence parties]]\n", "text_old": "{{Original research|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Wexit Canada\n| native_name =\n| slogan = \"The West Wants Out\"\n| _subheader =\n| logo = Wexitcanadablackandwhite.png\n| logo_size =\n| leader = Peter Downing\n| president =\n| spokesperson =\n| leader1_title =\n| leader1_name =\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|2020|01|12}}\n| dissolution =\n| merger =\n| split =\n| predecessor =\n| merged =\n| successor =\n| headquarters = [[Leduc, Alberta]]\n| ideology = {{ubl|[[Western alienation|Western separatism]]<ref name=\"The plan\"/><ref name=\"Wexit Party can now run for federal elections\"/>|[[Conservatism]]<ref name=\"Wexit rally\"/>|[[Right-wing populism]]}}\n| position = [[Far right-wing]]\n| national =\n| international =\n| student_wing =\n| membership =\n| membership_year =\n| colours = Black\n| colorcode = #000001\n| blank1_title = Fiscal policy\n| blank1 =\n| blank2_title = Social policy\n| blank2 =\n| seats2_title = Seats in the<br />[[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|0|105|hex=#000000}}\n| seats1_title = Seats in the <br>[[Senate of Canada|Senate]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|0|338|hex=#000000}}\n| website = {{URL|wexitcanada.com}}\n| country = Canada\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Wexit Canada''' is a Canadian [[List of federal political parties in Canada|federal political party]]. It advocates for the secession of [[Western Canada]], which includes [[British Columbia]], [[Alberta]], [[Saskatchewan]] and [[Manitoba]]. The name is a play on [[Brexit]], the withdrawal of the United Kingdom from the European Union.<ref>{{cite news |title='Wexit' should heed pitfalls faced by other separatist movements: experts |url=https://vancouverisland.ctvnews.ca/wexit-should-heed-pitfalls-faced-by-other-separatist-movements-experts-1.4741887 |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |publisher=[[CTV News]]}}</ref>\n\nThe party planned to run 104 candidates across the four provinces in 2020 and to run candidates for the provincial levels of government.<ref name=\"Wexit Party can now run for federal elections\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/wexit-peter-downing-western-separatism-elections-canada-1.5423793 |title=Wexit party granted eligibility for next federal election |last=Dryden |first=Joel |work=[[CBC News]] |date=January 11, 2020 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"FedProv\" /> The group initially gained traction in October 2019, shortly after the [[2019 Canadian federal election]], when the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]] under [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] [[Justin Trudeau]] was re-elected to form government.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Macvicar |first1=Adam |title=Wexit political party can now run candidates in Canadian federal elections |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6395322/wexit-political-partycanadian-federal-party-status/ |work=[[Global News]] |date=January 10, 2020 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bogart |first=Nicole |title=Wexit: How a political divide in Western Canada is driving calls for separation |url=https://election.ctvnews.ca/wexit-how-a-political-divide-in-western-canada-is-driving-calls-for-separation-1.4651085 |work=[[CTV News]] |date=October 22, 2019 |accessdate=January 13, 2020}}</ref> As of early 2020, the party started purchasing billboards in Alberta criticizing Trudeau, sparking public discussion over the lack of representation in western Canada.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://edmonton.ctvnews.ca/wexit-canada-becomes-eligible-federal-political-party-1.4763442 |title=Wexit Canada becomes eligible federal political party |last=Antoneshyn |first=Alex |website=CTV News Edmonton |date=January 12, 2020 |publisher=Bell Media |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> The party is currently led by former [[Christian Heritage Party of Canada|Christian Heritage]] candidate Peter Downing.<ref name=\"FedProv\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/wexit-rally-calgary-1.5362624 |title=Wexit party to run federal and provincial candidates across Western Canada |last=Rieger |first=Sarah |work=[[CBC News]] |date=November 17, 2019 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The party conducted a minor protest in [[Edmonton]], involving approximately 100 supporters.<ref name=\"Wexit rally\">{{Cite web |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6399314/wexit-referendum-edmonton-protest/ |title='We're looking for our own country': Wexit supporters brave cold in Edmonton for referendum protest Saturday |website=Global News |publisher=Corus Media |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Western separation ==\nWexit Canada's operators plan for their federal-level party to be used as a \"shield\" for smaller provincial operations. No [[member of parliament]] in the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] openly sympathizes with the idea of secession. The party wants a presence in the House to advance its goals. The party says it lacks enough momentum in [[Manitoba]] to achieve its goals there; however, it has larger pockets of support in the other three provinces.<ref name=\"The plan\">{{Cite web |url=http://wexitcanada.com/wexit-the-plan.pdf |title=Wexit The Plan |website=Wexit Canada |publisher=Wexit Canada |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Toneguzzi |first=Mario |title='Everyone\u2019s angry': Why you're wrong if you think Wexit is just 'an Alberta thing' |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/everyones-angry-why-youre-wrong-if-you-think-wexit-is-just-an-alberta-thing |date=November 26, 2019 |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |work=[[National Post]]}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n== Provincial parties ==\n\n=== Alberta ===\nThe Wexit Party is registered as a provincial party \"Wexit Alberta\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://wexitalberta.com/ |title=Wexit Alberta |website=Wexit Alberta |publisher=Wexit Alberta |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> According to its constitution, its plans include abolishing the provincial branch of the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police|RCMP]] and the establishment of an \"Alberta National Police\" and a \"Provincial Sheriff Program\". It plans to adopt an official currency to replace the [[Canadian dollar]] as well.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://wexitalberta.com/constitution.html |title=Wexit Alberta Constitution |publisher=Wexit Alberta |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://wexitalberta.com/platform.html |title=Wexit Alberta Platform |publisher=Wexit Alberta |access-date=February 3, 2020}}</ref> [[Barry Cooper (political scientist)|Barry Cooper]], a political scientist formerly of the [[University of Calgary]] who supports Western separation, said of western and eastern Canada's separate cultures in an interview with [[BBC]], \"It\u2019s a failure of trying to understand the other\u2014we don\u2019t share the same myths about what the country looks like, and we never have.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Levinson-King |first1=Robin |title=Wexit: Why some Albertans want to separate from Canada |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49899113 |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=October 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== British Columbia ===\nWexit BC is a registered party with [[Elections BC]]. Its leader is Lee Smith.<ref>{{cite web |last1=[[Elections BC]] |title=Registered Political Parties - Information |url=https://elections.bc.ca/docs/fin/Registered-Political-Parties-Information.pdf |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |work=[[Elections BC]] |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://wexitbc.org |title=Wexit British Columbia |website=Wexit British Columbia |publisher=Wexit British Columbia |date=2019 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Saskatchewan ===\nThe day after the 2019 federal election, [[Scott Moe]], [[premier of Saskatchewan]], proposed a \"New Deal\" with the federal government. He called for an end to the federal carbon tax, renegotiation of the equalization formula, and action on oil-pipeline projects.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/moe-new-deal-fire-western-alienation-1.5330659 |title=Premier Moe demands 'new deal,' says he is handing Justin Trudeau a 'fire extinguisher' |last=Hunter |first=Adam |work=[[CBC News]] |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> In the weeks after the election, Wexit volunteers began collecting signatures to form a new party. They called on Moe to hold a referendum on separation, saying that if he did not agree they would form a party to do so.<ref>{{Cite news |last=White-Crummey |first=Arthur |url=https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/wexit-party-registration-drive-coming-to-saskatchewan |title=Wexit party registration drive coming to Saskatchewan |work=[[Regina Leader-Post]] |date=November 8, 2019 |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Wiens |first=Colton |url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/wexit-saskatchewan-gathers-signatures-to-form-new-party-1.4689991 |title=Wexit Saskatchewan gathers signatures to form new party |work=[[CTV News]] |date=November 17, 2019 |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, 2020, Wexit Saskatchewan became registered as a provincial party with [[Elections Saskatchewan]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Charlton |first=Jonathan |url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/wexit-saskatchewan-gets-official-party-status-1.4847135 |title=Wexit Saskatchewan slams Moe, Sask Party as it applies for official party status |work=[[CTV News]] |date=March 10, 2020 |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=CBC News |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/wexit-saskatchewan-official-party-1.5492781 |title=Wexit Saskatchewan becomes official political party |work=[[CBC News]] |date=March 10, 2020 |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Its leader is Jake Wall.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Elections Saskatchewan |url=https://www.elections.sk.ca/candidates-political-parties/political-parties |title=Registered Political Parties |work=[[Elections Saskatchewan]] |date=2020 |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Elections Saskatchewan |url=https://cdn.elections.sk.ca/upload/RPP-Info-for-Website-2020.03.10.pdf |title=Registered Political Parties (as of March 10, 2020) |work=[[Elections Saskatchewan]] |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Once registered, Wexit Saskatchewan proposed a referendum on independence in its platform.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Wexit Saskatchewan |url=http://wexitsask.com/services.html |title=Platform |work=Wexit Saskatchewan |date=2020 |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Anti-Trudeau billboards ==\nIn early 2020, billboards that called for Trudeau's jailing appeared around Alberta, including [[Calgary]] and [[Edmonton]]. The billboards sparked an uproar and support on social media.<ref name=CTVCalgary/><ref name=\"CBC Calgary\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/trudeau-peter-downing-alberta-fights-back-signpatico-1.5424267 |title=After anti-Trudeau billboards spark outrage, ad company says it will re-evaluate vetting process |date=January 12, 2020 |access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> Those billboards pointed to the Wexit Party's website and were purchased though Signpatico, an advertising agency based in [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]]. Signpatico promised to vet future ads more carefully and stated, \"We do fundamentally stand by freedom of expression, as per the [[Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|charter]]. But we're not intending on inciting perceptions of hate speech or offensive ads.\"<ref name=\"CTVCalgary\">{{Cite news |url=https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/mobile/anti-trudeau-billboards-advertising-alberta-wexit-campaign-cause-an-uproar-1.4763332 |title=Anti-Trudeau billboards advertising Alberta Wexit campaign cause an uproar |last=Franklin |first=Michael |date=January 11, 2020 |work=CTV News |access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Canada|Politics}}\n* [[Western alienation]]\n* [[Alberta separatism]]\n* [[Cascadia (independence movement)]]\n* [[Western Block Party]]\n* [[Western Canada Concept]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Canadian federal political parties}}\n\n[[Category:2020 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2020]]\n[[Category:Secessionist organizations in Canada]]\n[[Category:Federal political parties in Canada]]\n[[Category:Regionalist parties]]\n[[Category:Pro-independence parties]]\n", "name_user": "VerifiedCactus", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wexit_Canada"}
